I would like to start a lean formalization of two things. 1. In this blog post: https://anthonylorenhart.com/2021-11-29-An-Optimal-and-Feasible-Pairing-Function/ I describe two pairing functions; I'd like the simpler of the two to be implemented and verified as a bijection in Lean. And in this post: https://anthonylorenhart.com/2021-01-08-Basic-Bijective-Godel-Encodings/ I describe a general scheme for turning descriptions of dependent inductive types into bijective codings. I'd like that to be turned into an actual formalization that shows that certain classes of dependent types defined as initial algebras of dependent polynomial functors can automatically be turned into bijections under mild conditions. This single general result should then be usable for the examples in the post as special cases. I'm not certain what the exact condition is, I'm hoping you'll be able to formulate it. Note that there are obvious solutions, punting to the existance of an isomorphism on the constructors, but, as the post points out in the end, that's where the difficulty lies so this is not really a useful answer (though it may be a useful theorem to prove anyway). The notes in the Trees of Bounded Height section about inverting changes on the output index seems closer to a useful characterization.
